 cols=2>
 <tr style='mso-yfti-irow:0;mso-yfti-firstrow:yes'>
  <td width="10%" valign=top style='width:10.0%;background:#33CCFF;padding:
  0in 0in 0in 0in'>
  <p align=center style='text-align:center'><b><a
  href="http://ethics.acusd.edu/">Ethics Resources</a></b> </p>
  </td>
  <td valign=top style='padding:0in 0in 0in 0in'>
  <h1 align=center style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:
  5.0pt;margin-left:.5in;text-align:center'>&nbsp;<span style='color:#000099'>Phil
  214: Introductory Ethics</span></h1>
  <p class=MsoNormal align=center style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;
  margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:.5in;text-align:center'><b><span
  style='font-size:13.5pt;color:#000099'>Course Syllabus</span></b></p>
  <p style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:
  .5in'><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Introduction</span></b> </p>
  <p style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:
  .5in'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>In this course we will grapple with some
  of the fundamental questions related to human conduct.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; How we
  should conduct ourselves?&nbsp; There are many different ways that we could
  respond to this question-- we will look at some of the most important
  approaches.&nbsp; We will see that some of them are better than others.&nbsp;
  <o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:
  .5in'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>One of the aims of this course is to
  consider important aspects of some different moral theories to put us in a
  position to determine what a plausible moral theory might look like.&nbsp;
  Another of our aims is to grapple with concrete moral questions that arise in
  disputes about lying, warfare, euthanasia and abortion etc..<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:
  .5in'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>You can find out more about the <b><a
  href="prodedure.html">course procedure</a></b> here. <o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:
  .5in'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>More detailed information about the
  course is found on the <b><a href="topics.html">course topics</a></b>
  page.&nbsp; This page contains links to assignments and audio lectures for
  both units of the course.&nbsp; This material will be modified and updated as
  the course progresses, so ask before you work ahead.&nbsp; In <b>Unit 1</b>
  we will examine the foundation of ethical theory.&nbsp; Is it plausible to
  think that there are objective truths in ethics that are binding for all
  human beings?&nbsp; Once we have dealt with that questions, we will look at
  the theories of John Stuart Mill, Immanuel Kant, and Thomas Aquinas to get
  some ideas about how to construct a moral theory.&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:
  .5in'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>In <b>Unit 2</b> we learn some of the
  most central concepts involved in Aristotle's virtue theory.&nbsp; We will
  spend more time on this theory than on any of the other theories because I
  find Aristotle's theory to be remarkably plausible and applicable.&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:
  .5in'><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>In <b>Unit 3</b> we focus directly on
  issues such as just war, pornography, euthanasia, and abortion.&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:
  .5in'><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Required Text</span></b><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt'><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:
  .5in'><u><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Exploring Ethics: An Introductory
  Anthology </span></u><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>&nbsp;edited by Steven
  Cahn&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:
  5.0pt;margin-left:1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l1 level1 lfo2;
  tab-stops:list .5in'><![if !supportLists]><span style='font-family:Symbol;
  mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
  style='mso-list:Ignore'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span></span><![endif]><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>This book is
  available in the UST bookstore or at <a
  href="http://www.amazon.com/Exploring-Ethics-Introductory-Steven-Cahn/dp/0195342003/ref=pd_bbs_sr_1?ie=UTF8&amp;s=books&amp;qid=1210692147&amp;sr=1-1">Amazon&nbsp;
  </a><o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:5.0pt;margin-left:
  .5in'><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Grading</span></b><span
  style='font-size:12.0pt'> <br>
  &nbsp; <o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:
  5.0pt;margin-left:1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo4;
  tab-stops:list .5in'><![if !supportLists]><span style='font-family:Symbol;
  mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
  style='mso-list:Ignore'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span></span><![endif]><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>You will asked
  to write 4 <b><a href="analyticpapers.html">short analytic papers</a> </b>on topics
  related to course content.&nbsp; Each paper is to be written according to a
  format that is explained on the page about papers.&nbsp; Each paper is worth
  20 points, which constitutes 40% of your final grade<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:
  5.0pt;margin-left:1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo4;
  tab-stops:list .5in'><![if !supportLists]><span style='font-family:Symbol;
  mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
  style='mso-list:Ignore'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span></span><![endif]><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Regular
  participation</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt'> in our discussion
  forum in Blackboard will be critical component of this course.&nbsp; You will
  be required to make a minimum of 5 contributions per week to the forum.&nbsp;
  A maximum of 5 points are awarded for participation for each week of
  class.&nbsp; Participation is graded in terms of quantity and quality.&nbsp;
  I want to see posts spread out over the week.&nbsp; I would like some of your
  posts to be responses to other students, and for some to be questions or
  comments of your own.&nbsp; 5 postings brief postings on Sunday night will
  earn a low participation score for that week.&nbsp; 5 postings spread
  throughout the week that show you have reflected on the material will earn a
  high score for that week.&nbsp; Participation constitutes 27.5% of the final
  grade<o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:
  5.0pt;margin-left:1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo4;
  tab-stops:list .5in'><![if !supportLists]><span style='font-family:Symbol;
  mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
  style='mso-list:Ignore'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span></span><![endif]><b><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>Weekly
  assignments</span></b><span style='font-size:12.0pt'> are comprised of
  questions about the readings we will cover.&nbsp; Assignments are worth 25%
  of the final grade.&nbsp; Each assignment is worth a maximum of 5
  points.&nbsp; I will provide these assignments at the start of each
  week.&nbsp; 5 points will be awarded for exemplary work.&nbsp; 4 for good
  work.&nbsp; 3 for fair work.&nbsp; 2 for poor. 1 for late work.&nbsp;&nbsp;
  Thorough, reflective responses to weekly assignment questions are expected,
  but this may not be sufficient to earn a score of 5, which is reserved for
  truly outstanding work.&nbsp; <o:p></o:p></span></p>
  <p class=MsoNormal style='margin-top:5.0pt;margin-right:.5in;margin-bottom:
  5.0pt;margin-left:1.0in;text-indent:-.25in;mso-list:l0 level1 lfo4;
  tab-stops:list .5in'><![if !supportLists]><span style='font-family:Symbol;
  mso-fareast-font-family:Symbol;mso-bidi-font-family:Symbol'><span
  style='mso-list:Ignore'>·<span style='font:7.0pt "Times New Roman"'>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
  </span></span></span><![endif]><span style='font-size:12.0pt'>There will be 3
  <b>logic quizzes</b> near the start of the course to make sure that students
  have basic skill needed for writing the papers.&nbsp; These times quizzes
  will be worth 5 points each.&nbsp; These quizzes are worth 7.5% of your final
  grade.<o:p></o:p></span></p>
